[
    {
        "content": "<p>I feel like we should have a function <br>\n<code> pow (a x : \\R) \\to \\R </code> which is equal to 0 (or 37 :) ) if a is negative and agrees with <code> exp(x log a) </code> otherwise</p>",
        "id": 195780626,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1588201241
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe the thing I said is already the right definition</p>",
        "id": 195780691,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1588201302
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If we had this function, would it make sense to use it an as instance of <code>has_pow \\R \\R</code> ?</p>",
        "id": 195780767,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1588201355
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess I'm still asking a silly question, I can just try to do this</p>",
        "id": 195780820,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1588201397
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There has been some discussion of powers in the past, including some debunking of attempts to attach a meaning to various notions of powers, but the Riemann zeta function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ζ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>s</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\zeta(s)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07378em;\">ζ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">s</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is defined, for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">s</span></span></span></span> a complex number with real part greater than one, to be the infinite sum <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mn>1</mn><mi>s</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>s</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>3</mn><mi>s</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mo>⋯</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1^s+2^s+3^s+\\cdots</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.747722em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">s</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.747722em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">s</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.747722em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">3</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">s</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.31em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">⋯</span></span></span></span> and here the convention is that if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span></span></span></span> is a positive real and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">s</span></span></span></span> is a complex number then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>r</mi><mi>s</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r^s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.664392em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">s</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is defined as <code>exp(s log r)</code> and this function has good properties. For <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r\\leq0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719400000000001em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> it's a nightmare and you probably want to let it be zero -- but here's the catch! If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span></span></span></span> is a negative real and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">s</span></span></span></span> is an <em>integer</em> then <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>r</mi><mi>s</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">r^s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.664392em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">r</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault mtight\">s</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> makes perfect sense and isn't zero, so one would have to be careful with coercions.</p>",
        "id": 195781852,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1588202137
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess the coercion claim can be made subject to hypotheses, analogous to claims about subtraction on naturals and integers only being equal under an inequality assumption</p>",
        "id": 195781966,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1588202210
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So in summary I would be happy to see it as an instance for <code>has_pow \\R \\C</code> and <code>has_pow \\R \\R</code> with the convention that it's zero if r&lt;0</p>",
        "id": 195782079,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1588202302
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's hard to imagine someone taking a negative number to a negative integer power and then wanting to coerce the integer to a real and expecting good things to happen</p>",
        "id": 195782132,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1588202356
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually after the change in log today one could let the log definition work for all nonzero r</p>",
        "id": 195782401,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1588202549
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There already is a real to the power real instance.</p>",
        "id": 195782420,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1588202569
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't remember it's junk behaviour.</p>",
        "id": 195782459,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1588202590
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It might have actually just changed now that log changed.</p>",
        "id": 195782555,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Hughes",
        "timestamp": 1588202646
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh you can't have R to C to C for a power!</p>",
        "id": 195782759,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1588202824
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110044\">Chris Hughes</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there.20code.20for.20X.3F/topic/real.20powers.20of.20positive.20reals.3F/near/195782420\" title=\"#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there.20code.20for.20X.3F/topic/real.20powers.20of.20positive.20reals.3F/near/195782420\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>There already is a real to the power real instance.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Where is it defined? I don't have it with this import list:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">data</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">real</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">basic</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">data</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">complex</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">exponential</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">import</span> <span class=\"n\">analysis</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">asymptotics</span>\n\n<span class=\"bp\">#</span><span class=\"kn\">check</span> <span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">^</span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span> <span class=\"o\">:</span> <span class=\"n\">ℝ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 195786252,
        "sender_full_name": "Jalex Stark",
        "timestamp": 1588205735
    },
